# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: concurrency
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:concurrency/async-await] In computer programming, the **async/await pattern** is a syntactic feature of many programming languages that allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:concurrency/async-await] The feature is found in C#, C++, Python, F#, Hack, Julia, Dart, Kotlin, Rust, Nim, JavaScript, and Swift.
[src:concurrency/async-await] F# added asynchronous workflows with await points in version 2.0 in 2007.
[src:concurrency/async-await] This influenced the async/await mechanism added to C#.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Haskell lead developer Simon Marlow created the async package in 2010.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Microsoft first released a version of C# with async/await in the Async CTP (2011).
[src:concurrency/async-await] It was later officially released in C# 5 (2012).
[src:concurrency/async-await] Python added support for async/await with version 3.5 in 2015 adding 2 new keywords, `async` and `await`.
[src:concurrency/async-await] TypeScript added support for async/await with version 1.7 in 2015.
[src:concurrency/async-await] JavaScript added support for async/await in 2017 as part of ECMAScript 2017 JavaScript edition.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Rust added support for async/await with version 1.39.0 in 2019 using the `async` keyword and the `.await` postfix operator, both introduced in the 2018 edition of the language.
[src:concurrency/async-await] C++ added support for async/await with version 20 in 2020 with 3 new keywords `co_return`, `co_await`, `co_yield`.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Swift added support for async/await with version 5.5 in 2021, adding 2 new keywords `async` and `await`.
[src:concurrency/async-await] This was released alongside a concrete implementation of the Actor model with the `actor` keyword which uses async/await to mediate access to each actor from outside.
[src:concurrency/async-await] A function using async/await can use as many `await` expressions as it wants, and each will be handled in the same way (though a promise will only be returned to the caller for the first await, while every other await will utilize internal callbacks).
[src:concurrency/async-await] A function can also hold a promise object directly and do other processing first (including starting other asynchronous tasks), delaying awaiting the promise until its result is needed.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Functions with promises also have promise aggregation methods that allow the program to await multiple promises at once or in some special pattern (such as C#'s `Task.WhenAll()`, which returns a valueless `Task` that resolves when all of the tasks in the arguments have resolved).
[src:concurrency/async-await] Many promise types also have additional features beyond what the async/await pattern normally uses, such as being able to set up more than one result callback or inspect the progress of an especially long-running task.
[src:concurrency/async-await] In the particular case of C#, and in many other languages with this language feature, the async/await pattern is not a core part of the language's runtime, but is instead implemented with lambdas or continuations at compile time.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Because of this, if an interface method needs to return a promise object, but itself does not require `await` in the body to wait on any asynchronous tasks, it does not need the `async` modifier either and can instead return a promise object directly.
[src:concurrency/async-await] For instance, a function might be able to provide a promise that immediately resolves to some result value (such as C#'s `Task.FromResult()`), or it may simply return another method's promise that happens to be the exact promise needed (such as when deferring to an overload).
[src:concurrency/async-await] One important caveat of this functionality, however, is that while the code resembles traditional blocking code, the code is actually non-blocking and potentially multithreaded, meaning that many intervening events may occur while waiting for the promise targeted by an `await` to resolve.
[src:concurrency/async-await] The C language does not support await/async.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Some coroutine libraries such as *s_task* simulate the keywords await/async with macros.
[src:concurrency/async-await] In C++, await (named `co_await` in C++ to emphasise its context in coroutines) has been officially merged into C++20.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Support for it, coroutines, and the keywords such as `co_await` are available in GCC and MSVC compilers while Clang has partial support.
[src:concurrency/async-await] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:concurrency/async-await] To call it, use `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:concurrency/async-await] It is worth noting that `std::promise` and `std::future`, although it would seem that they would be awaitable objects, implement none of the machinery required to be returned from coroutines and be awaited using `co_await`.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Programmers must implement a number of public member functions, such as `await_ready`, `await_suspend`, and `await_resume` on the return type in order for the type to be awaited on.
[src:concurrency/async-await] In 2012, C# added the async/await pattern in C# with version 5.0, which Microsoft refers to as the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP).
[src:concurrency/async-await] Async methods usually return either `void`, `Task`, `Task<T>`, `ValueTask` or `ValueTask<T>`.
[src:concurrency/async-await] User code can define custom types that async methods can return through custom *async method builders* but this is an advanced and rare scenario.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Async methods that return `void` are intended for event handlers; in most cases where a synchronous method would return `void`, returning `Task` instead is recommended, as it allows for more intuitive exception handling (note that `Task<void>` is invalid in C#).
[src:concurrency/async-await] Methods that make use of `await` must be declared with the `async` keyword.
[src:concurrency/async-await] In methods that have a return value of type `Task<T>`, methods declared with `async` must have a return statement of type assignable to `T` instead of `Task<T>`; the compiler wraps the value in the `Task<T>` generic.
[src:concurrency/async-await] It is also possible to `await` methods that have a return type of `Task` or `Task<T>` that are declared without `async`.
[src:concurrency/async-await] The following async method downloads data from a URL using `await`.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Because this method issues a task for each URI before requiring completion with the `await` keyword, the resources can load at the same time instead of waiting for the last resource to finish before starting to load the next.
[src:concurrency/async-await] In 2007, F# added asynchronous workflows with version 2.0.
[src:concurrency/async-await] The asynchronous workflows are implemented as CE (computation expressions).
[src:concurrency/async-await] They can be defined without specifying any special context (like `async` in C#).
[src:concurrency/async-await] F# asynchronous workflows append a bang (!) to keywords to start asynchronous tasks.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Java does not have `async` and `await` keywords in the language, however it can be emulated using the `java.util.concurrent` package, such as the class `CompletableFuture` (introduced in Java 8).
[src:concurrency/async-await] Asynchronous programming is later improved in Java 21 with the introduction of virtual threads and structured task scopes.
[src:concurrency/async-await] The await operator in JavaScript (and TypeScript) can only be used from inside an async function or at the top level of a module.
[src:concurrency/async-await] If the parameter is a promise, execution of the async function will resume when the promise is resolved (unless the promise is rejected, in which case an error will be thrown that can be handled with normal JavaScript exception handling).
[src:concurrency/async-await] If the parameter is not a promise, the parameter itself will be returned immediately.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Many libraries provide promise objects that can also be used with await, as long as they match the specification for native JavaScript promises.
[src:concurrency/async-await] However, promises from the jQuery library were not Promises/A+ compatible until jQuery 3.0.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Node.js version 8 includes a utility that enables using the standard library callback-based methods as promises.
[src:concurrency/async-await] The Future::AsyncAwait module was the subject of a Perl Foundation grant in September 2018.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Python 3.5 (2015) has added support for async/await as described in PEP 492 (written and implemented by Yury Selivanov).
[src:concurrency/async-await] On November 7, 2019, async/await was released on the stable version of Rust.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Async functions in Rust desugar to plain functions that return values that implement the Future trait.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Currently they are implemented with a finite-state machine.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Swift 5.5 (2021) added support for async/await as described in SE-0296.
[src:concurrency/async-await] The async/await pattern is especially attractive to language designers of languages that do not have or control their own runtime, as async/await can be implemented solely as a transformation to a state machine in the compiler.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Supporters claim that asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written with async/await that looks almost like traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:concurrency/async-await] In particular, it has been argued that await is the best way of writing asynchronous code in message-passing programs; in particular, being close to blocking code, readability and the minimal amount of boilerplate code were cited as await benefits.
[src:concurrency/async-await] Critics of async/await note that the pattern tends to cause surrounding code to be asynchronous too; and that its contagious nature splits languages' library ecosystems between synchronous and asynchronous libraries and APIs, an issue often referred to as "function coloring".
[src:concurrency/async-await] Alternatives to async/await that do not suffer from this issue are called "colorless".
[src:concurrency/async-await] Examples of colorless designs include Go's goroutines and Java's virtual threads.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] In concurrent computing, **deadlock** is any situation in which no member of some group of entities can proceed because each waits for another member, including itself, to take action, such as sending a message or, more commonly, releasing a lock.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlocks are a common problem in multiprocessing systems, parallel computing, and distributed systems, because in these contexts systems often use software or hardware locks to arbitrate shared resources and implement process synchronization.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] In an operating system, a deadlock occurs when a process or thread enters a waiting state because a requested system resource is held by another waiting process, which in turn is waiting for another resource held by another waiting process.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] If a process remains indefinitely unable to change its state because resources requested by it are being used by another process that itself is waiting, then the system is said to be in a deadlock.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] In a communications system, deadlocks occur mainly due to loss or corruption of signals rather than contention for resources.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] *Hold and wait* or *resource holding:* a process is currently holding at least one resource and requesting additional resources which are being held by other processes.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] *No preemption:* a resource can be released only voluntarily by the process holding it.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] *Circular wait:* each process must be waiting for a resource which is being held by another process, which in turn is waiting for the first process to release the resource.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] In general, there is a set of waiting processes, *P* = {*P*1, *P*2, ..., *P**N*}, such that *P*1 is waiting for a resource held by *P*2, *P*2 is waiting for a resource held by *P*3 and so on until *P**N* is waiting for a resource held by *P*1.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] These four conditions are known as the *Coffman conditions* from their first description in a 1971 article by Edward G.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] While these conditions are sufficient to produce a deadlock on single-instance resource systems, they only indicate the possibility of deadlock on systems having multiple instances of resources.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Most current operating systems cannot prevent deadlocks.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] When a deadlock occurs, different operating systems respond to them in different non-standard manners.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Most approaches work by preventing one of the four *Coffman conditions* from occurring, especially the fourth one.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] In this approach, it is assumed that a deadlock will never occur.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] This is also an application of the Ostrich algorithm.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] This approach was initially used by MINIX and UNIX.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] This is used when the time intervals between occurrences of deadlocks are large and the data loss incurred each time is tolerable.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Ignoring deadlocks can be safely done if deadlocks are formally proven to never occur.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Under the deadlock detection, deadlocks are allowed to occur.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Then the state of the system is examined to detect that a deadlock has occurred and subsequently it is corrected.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] An algorithm is employed that tracks resource allocation and process states, it rolls back and restarts one or more of the processes in order to remove the detected deadlock.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Detecting a deadlock that has already occurred is easily possible since the resources that each process has locked and/or currently requested are known to the resource scheduler of the operating system.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] *Resource preemption:* resources allocated to various processes may be successively preempted and allocated to other processes until the deadlock is broken.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock prevention works by preventing one of the four Coffman conditions from occurring.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Similar to deadlock prevention, deadlock avoidance approach ensures that deadlock will not occur in a system.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] The term "deadlock avoidance" appears to be very close to "deadlock prevention" in a linguistic context, but they are very much different in the context of deadlock handling.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock avoidance does not impose any conditions as seen in prevention but, here each resource request is carefully analyzed to see whether it could be safely fulfilled without causing deadlock.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock avoidance requires that the operating system be given in advance additional information concerning which resources a process will request and use during its lifetime.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock avoidance algorithm analyzes each and every request by examining that there is no possibility of deadlock occurrence in the future if the requested resource is allocated.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] The drawback of this approach is its requirement of information in advance about how resources are to be requested in the future.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] One of the most used deadlock avoidance algorithms is Banker's algorithm.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] A *livelock* is similar to a deadlock, except that the states of the processes involved in the livelock constantly change with regard to one another, none progressing.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Ashcroft in a 1975 paper in connection with an examination of airline booking systems.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Livelock is a special case of resource starvation; the general definition only states that a specific process is not progressing.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Livelock is a risk with some algorithms that detect and recover from *deadlock*.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] If more than one process takes action, the deadlock detection algorithm can be repeatedly triggered.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] This can be avoided by ensuring that only one process (chosen arbitrarily or by priority) takes action.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Unlike in centralized systems, detecting and resolving distributed deadlocks is more complex due to the lack of shared memory and the need for coordination among nodes.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] Techniques like wait-for graphs, distributed algorithms (like edge chasing; e.g., Chandy-Misra-Haas), and deadlock prevention (e.g., timeout-based methods) are used to handle such scenarios.
[src:concurrency/deadlock-computer-science] The challenge lies in ensuring consistency and avoiding false positives/negatives due to network delays or partial failures.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In software, an **event loop** is an algorithm that continually dispatches control flow for events.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] The loop requests the next event from an event provider (which generally blocks the loop until an event occurs), and when an event is received, invokes its associated event handler.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] When the event loop is the central event dispatcher of a program, as it often is, it is called the **main loop** or **main event loop**.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In modern environments such as web browsers and server runtimes, the event loop is a fundamental mechanism that enables asynchronous execution by continuously monitoring and dispatching events or messages from a queue when the main program thread is idle.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In JavaScript, the event loop allows non-blocking handling of tasks such as user interactions, timers, and I/O operations despite the language being single-threaded.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] The same algorithm can be used to process inbound messages, a superset of events.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In this context, the algorithm is called a **message loop**, **message dispatcher**, or **message pump**.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] A common use for a message loop is message passing inter-process communication where the message queue is maintained outside of the program (such as by the operating system).
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Typically, a program that operates in a graphical user interface (GUI) environment uses an event loop, and due to the predominance of GUI environments, most modern applications have a main event loop.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In the following pseudocode, `get_next_message()` is a placeholder for a function that is typically provided by the operating system that blocks until a message is available.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Thus, the loop only repeats when there is a message to process.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Many programs include an event loop in the high-level design; a main event loop, but there are alternative designs.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] A program can exit as soon as it completes the actions that it's designed to do without external (i.e. user) interaction.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Often, such a program has optional behavior that is set up before the program starts such as via the command-line interface (CLI) or environment variables.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Utility software is often of this nature.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Even if a program provides for user interaction, it might not use an event loop.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] A program that provides an internal CLI does include a command processor that is similar to an event loop in that it dispatches to command handlers based on user input.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] A web page and its JavaScript typically run in a single-threaded web browser process.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] The browser process deals with messages from a queue one at a time.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] A JavaScript function or another browser event might be associated with a given message.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] When the browser process has finished with a message, it proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In JavaScript environments, the event loop works with separate queues — including a task queue and a microtask queue — to manage asynchronous operations such as timers, promise callbacks, and DOM events.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] When the call stack is empty, the event loop selects the next task from these queues to execute.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In Windows, a process that interacts with the user must accept and react to incoming messages, which is almost inevitably done by a message loop in that process.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In Windows, a message is equated to an event created and imposed upon the operating system.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] An event can be user interaction, network traffic, system processing, timer activity, inter-process communication, among others.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] For non-interactive, I/O only events, Windows has I/O completion ports.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] I/O completion port loops run separately from the Message loop, and do not interact with the Message loop out of the box.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] The heart of most Win32 applications is the WinMain() function, which calls GetMessage() in a loop.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] GetMessage() blocks until a message (event), is received (with function PeekMessage() as a non-blocking alternative).
[src:concurrency/event-loop] After some optional processing, it will call DispatchMessage(), which dispatches the message to the relevant handler, also known as WindowProc.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Normally, messages that have no special WindowProc() are dispatched to DefWindowProc, the default one.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] DispatchMessage() calls the WindowProc of the HWND handle of the message (registered with the RegisterClass() function).
[src:concurrency/event-loop] More recent versions of Windows guarantee that messages will be delivered to an application's message loop in the order that they were perceived by the system and its peripherals.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] This guarantee is essential when considering the design consequences of multithreaded applications.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] However, some messages have different rules, such as messages that are always received last, or messages with a different documented priority.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] X applications using Xlib directly are built around the `XNextEvent` family of functions; `XNextEvent` blocks until an event appears on the event queue, whereupon the application processes it appropriately.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] The Xlib event loop only handles window system events; applications that need to be able to wait on other files and devices could construct their own event loop from primitives such as `ConnectionNumber`, but in practice tend to use multithreading.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In the more common case, GUI toolkits based on Xlib usually support adding events.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] For example, toolkits based on Xt Intrinsics have `XtAppAddInput()` and `XtAppAddTimeout()`.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] It is not safe to call Xlib functions from a signal handler, because the X application may have been interrupted in an arbitrary state, e.g. within `XNextEvent`.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] See [1] for a solution for X11R5, X11R6 and Xt.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] The GLib event loop was originally created for use in GTK but is now used in non-GUI applications as well, such as D-Bus.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] The resource polled is the collection of file descriptors the application is interested in; the polling block will be interrupted if a signal arrives or a timeout expires (e.g. if the application has specified a timeout or idle task).
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Application libraries that are built on the GLib event loop include GStreamer and the asynchronous I/O methods of GnomeVFS, but GTK remains the most visible client library.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Events from the windowing system (in X, read off the X socket) are translated by GDK into GTK events and emitted as GLib signals on the application's widget objects.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Exactly one CFRunLoop is allowed per thread, and arbitrarily many sources and observers can be attached.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Sources then communicate with observers through the run loop, with it organising queueing and dispatch of messages.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] The CFRunLoop is abstracted in Cocoa as an NSRunLoop, which allows any message (equivalent to a function call in non-reflective runtimes) to be queued for dispatch to any object.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In Unix, the everything is a file paradigm leads to a file-based event loop.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Reading from and writing to files, inter-process communication, network communication, and device control are all achieved using file I/O, with the target identified by a file descriptor.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] The select and poll system calls allow a set of file descriptors to be monitored for a change of state, e.g. when data becomes available to be read.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In Unix, a signal is an asynchronous event that is handled by a signal handler which runs while the rest of the task is suspended.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] If a signal is received and handled while the task is blocking in `select()`, select will return early with EINTR; if a signal is received while the task is CPU bound, the task will be suspended between instructions until the signal handler returns.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] A way to handle a signal is for signal handlers to set a global flag and have the event loop check for the flag immediately before and after the `select()` call; if it is set, handle the signal in the same manner as with events on file descriptors.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Unfortunately, this gives rise to a race condition: if a signal arrives immediately between checking the flag and calling `select()`, it will not be handled until `select()` returns for some other reason (for example, being interrupted by a frustrated user).
[src:concurrency/event-loop] The solution arrived at by POSIX is the `pselect()` call, which is similar to `select()` but takes an additional `sigmask` parameter, which describes a *signal mask*.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] This allows an application to mask signals in the main task, then remove the mask for the duration of the `select()` call such that signal handlers are only called while the application is I/O bound.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] However, implementations of `pselect()` have not always been reliable; versions of Linux prior to 2.6.16 do not have a `pselect()` system call, forcing glibc to emulate it via a method prone to the very same race condition `pselect()` is intended to avoid.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] An alternative, more portable solution, is to convert asynchronous events to file-based events using the *self-pipe trick*, where "a signal handler writes a byte to a pipe whose other end is monitored by `select()` in the main program".
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In Linux kernel version 2.6.22, a new system call `signalfd()` was added, which allows receiving signals via a special file descriptor.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] In environments such as web browsers and Node.js, the event loop is central to asynchronous program behavior.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] JavaScript runs on a single thread for execution, but host environments provide APIs for non-blocking operations, such as timers, network requests, and user events.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] Completed asynchronous operations are placed in queues, and the event loop repeatedly checks whether the call stack is empty to schedule queued callbacks.
[src:concurrency/event-loop] This enables JavaScript applications to remain responsive while handling multiple asynchronous tasks.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] In computer science, **futures**, **promises**, **delays**, and **deferreds** are constructs used for synchronizing program execution in some concurrent programming languages.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Each is an object that acts as a proxy for a result that is initially unknown, usually because the computation of its value is not yet complete.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was proposed in 1976 by Daniel P.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Friedman and David Wise, and Peter Hibbard called it *eventual*.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] A somewhat similar concept *future* was introduced in 1977 in a paper by Henry Baker and Carl Hewitt.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The terms *future*, *promise*, *delay*, and *deferred* are often used interchangeably, although there can be some differences in usage between *future* and *promise*.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Specifically, when usage is distinguished, a future is a *read-only* placeholder view of a variable, while a promise is a writable, single assignment container which sets the value of the future.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Notably, a future may be defined without specifying which specific promise will set its value, and different possible promises may set the value of a given future, though this can be done only once for a given future.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] In other cases a future and a promise are created together and associated with each other: the future is the value, the promise is the function that sets the value – essentially the return value (future) of an asynchronous function (promise).
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Setting the value of a future is also called *resolving*, *fulfilling*, or *binding* it.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Futures and promises originated in functional programming and related paradigms (such as logic programming) to decouple a value (a future) from how it was computed (a promise), allowing the computation to be done more flexibly, notably by parallelizing it.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Later, it found use in distributed computing, in reducing the latency from communication round trips.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Later still, it gained more use by allowing writing asynchronous programs in direct style, rather than in continuation-passing style.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Use of futures may be *implicit* (any use of the future automatically obtains its value, as if it were an ordinary reference) or *explicit* (the user must call a function to obtain the value, such as the `get` method of `java.util.concurrent.Future`in Java).
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Obtaining the value of an explicit future can be called *stinging* or *forcing*.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Explicit futures can be implemented as a library, whereas implicit futures are usually implemented as part of the language.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The original Baker and Hewitt paper described implicit futures, which are naturally supported in the actor model of computation and pure object-oriented programming languages like Smalltalk.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The Friedman and Wise paper described only explicit futures, probably reflecting the difficulty of efficiently implementing implicit futures on stock hardware.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The difficulty is that stock hardware does not deal with futures for primitive data types like integers.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] For example, an add instruction does not know how to deal with `3 + *future* factorial(100000)`.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] In pure actor or object languages this problem can be solved by sending `*future* factorial(100000)` the message `+[3]`, which asks the future to add `3` to itself and return the result.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Note that the message passing approach works regardless of when `factorial(100000)` finishes computation and that no stinging/forcing is needed.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The use of futures can dramatically reduce latency in distributed systems.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] For instance, futures enable *promise pipelining*, as implemented in the languages E and Joule, which was also called *call-stream* in the language Argus.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Each statement needs a message to be sent and a reply received before the next statement can proceed.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Suppose, for example, that `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] In this case, two complete network round-trips to that machine must take place before the third statement can begin to execute.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The third statement will then cause yet another round-trip to the same remote machine.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The syntax used here is that of the language E, where `x <- a()` means to send the message `a()` asynchronously to `x`.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] All three variables are immediately assigned futures for their results, and execution proceeds to subsequent statements.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Later attempts to resolve the value of `t3` may cause a delay; however, pipelining can reduce the number of round-trips needed.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] If, as in the prior example, `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine, a pipelined implementation can compute `t3` with one round-trip instead of three.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Because all three messages are destined for objects which are on the same remote machine, only one request need be sent and only one response need be received containing the result.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The send `t1 <- c(t2)` would not block even if `t1` and `t2` were on different machines to each other, or to `x` or `y`.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining should be distinguished from parallel asynchronous message passing.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The relative latency advantage of pipelining becomes even greater in more complicated situations involving many messages.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining also should not be confused with pipelined message processing in actor systems, where it is possible for an actor to specify and begin executing a behaviour for the next message before having completed processing of the current message.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Support for read-only views is consistent with the principle of least privilege, since it enables the ability to set the value to be restricted to subjects that need to set it.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] In a system that also supports pipelining, the sender of an asynchronous message (with result) receives the read-only promise for the result, and the target of the message receives the resolver.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Some languages, such as Alice ML, define futures that are associated with a specific thread that computes the future's value.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] This computation can start either eagerly when the future is created, or lazily when its value is first needed.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] A lazy future is similar to a thunk, in the sense of a delayed computation.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Alice ML also supports futures that can be resolved by any thread, and calls these *promises*.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] This use of *promise* is different from its use in E as described above.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] In Alice, a promise is not a read-only view, and promise pipelining is unsupported.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Instead, pipelining naturally happens for futures, including ones associated with promises.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] If the value of a future is accessed asynchronously, for example by sending a message to it, or by explicitly waiting for it using a construct such as `when` in E, then there is no difficulty in delaying until the future is resolved before the message can be received or the wait completes.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] This is the only case to be considered in purely asynchronous systems such as pure actor languages.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] However, in some systems it may also be possible to attempt to *immediately* or *synchronously* access a future's value.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] As an example of the first possibility, in C++11, a thread that needs the value of a future can block until it is available by calling the `wait()` or `get()` member functions.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] A timeout can also be specified on the wait using the `wait_for()` or `wait_until()` member functions to avoid indefinite blocking.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] If the future arose from a call to `std::async` then a blocking wait (without a timeout) may cause synchronous invocation of the function to compute the result on the waiting thread.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] An *I-var* (as in the language Id) is a future with blocking semantics as defined above.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] An *I-structure* is a data structure containing I-vars.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] A related synchronization construct that can be set multiple times with different values is called an *M-var*.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] M-vars support atomic operations to *take* or *put* the current value, where taking the value also sets the M-var back to its initial *empty* state.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent logic variable* is similar to a future, but is updated by unification, in the same way as *logic variables* in logic programming.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Thus it can be bound more than once to unifiable values, but cannot be set back to an empty or unresolved state.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The dataflow variables of Oz act as concurrent logic variables, and also have blocking semantics as mentioned above.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent constraint variable* is a generalization of concurrent logic variables to support constraint logic programming: the constraint may be *narrowed* multiple times, indicating smaller sets of possible values.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Typically there is a way to specify a thunk that should run whenever the constraint is narrowed further; this is needed to support *constraint propagation*.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Eager thread-specific futures can be straightforwardly implemented in non-thread-specific futures, by creating a thread to calculate the value at the same time as creating the future.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] In this case it is desirable to return a read-only view to the client, so that only the newly created thread is able to resolve this future.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] To implement implicit lazy thread-specific futures (as provided by Alice ML, for example) in terms in non-thread-specific futures, needs a mechanism to determine when the future's value is first needed (for example, the `WaitNeeded` construct in Oz).
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] If all values are objects, then the ability to implement transparent forwarding objects is sufficient, since the first message sent to the forwarder indicates that the future's value is needed.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Non-thread-specific futures can be implemented in thread-specific futures, assuming that the system supports message passing, by having the resolving thread send a message to the future's own thread.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] However, this can be viewed as unneeded complexity.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] In programming languages based on threads, the most expressive approach seems to be to provide a mix of non-thread-specific futures, read-only views, and either a *WaitNeeded* construct, or support for transparent forwarding.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The evaluation strategy of futures, which may be termed *call by future*, is non-deterministic: the value of a future will be evaluated at some time between when the future is created and when its value is used, but the precise time is not determined beforehand and can change from run to run.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The computation can start as soon as the future is created (eager evaluation) or only when the value is actually needed (lazy evaluation), and may be suspended part-way through, or executed in one run.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Once the value of a future is assigned, it is not recomputed on future accesses; this is like the memoization used in call by need.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] A **lazy future** is a future that deterministically has lazy evaluation semantics: the computation of the future's value starts when the value is first needed, as in call by need.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Lazy futures are of use in languages which evaluation strategy is by default not lazy.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] For example, in C++11 such lazy futures can be created by passing the `std::launch::deferred` launch policy to `std::async`, along with the function to compute the value.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] If it does not already have a response, then *R* is stored in the queue of requests inside the *F*.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] However, some futures can deal with requests in special ways to provide greater parallelism.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] For example, the expression `1 + future factorial(n)` can create a new future that will behave like the number `1+factorial(n)`.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] suspends until the future for `factorial(n)` has responded to the request asking if `m` is greater than itself.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The *future* and/or *promise* constructs were first implemented in programming languages such as MultiLisp and Act 1.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The use of logic variables for communication in concurrent logic programming languages was quite similar to futures.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] These began in *Prolog with Freeze* and *IC Prolog*, and became a true concurrency primitive with Relational Language, Concurrent Prolog, guarded Horn clauses (GHC), Parlog, Strand, Vulcan, Janus, Oz-Mozart, Flow Java, and Alice ML.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The single-assignment *I-var* from dataflow programming languages, originating in Id and included in Reppy's *Concurrent ML*, is much like the concurrent logic variable.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The promise pipelining technique (using futures to overcome latency) was invented by Barbara Liskov and Liuba Shrira in 1988, and independently by Mark S.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Miller, Dean Tribble and Rob Jellinghaus in the context of Project Xanadu circa 1989.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was coined by Liskov and Shrira, although they referred to the pipelining mechanism by the name *call-stream*, which is now rarely used.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] It seems that promises and call-streams were never implemented in any public release of Argus, the programming language used in the Liskov and Shrira paper.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The Xanadu implementation of promise pipelining only became publicly available with the release of the source code for Udanax Gold in 1999, and was never explained in any published document.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The later implementations in Joule and E support fully first-class promises and resolvers.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Several early actor languages, including the Act series, supported both parallel message passing and pipelined message processing, but not promise pipelining.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] After 2000, a major revival of interest in futures and promises occurred, due to their use in responsiveness of user interfaces, and in web development, due to the request–response model of message-passing.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] This has subsequently been adopted by other languages, notably Dart (2014), Python (2015), Hack (HHVM), and drafts of ECMAScript 7 (JavaScript), Scala, and C++ (2011).
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Some programming languages are supporting futures, promises, concurrent logic variables, dataflow variables, or I-vars, either by direct language support or in the standard library.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Futures can be implemented in coroutines or generators, resulting in the same evaluation strategy (e.g., cooperative multitasking or lazy evaluation).
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] Futures can easily be implemented in channels: a future is a one-element channel, and a promise is a process that sends to the channel, fulfilling the future.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] This allows futures to be implemented in concurrent programming languages with support for channels, such as CSP and Go.
[src:concurrency/futures-and-promises] The resulting futures are explicit, as they must be accessed by reading from the channel, rather than only evaluation.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] In computer science, **mutual exclusion** is a property of concurrency control, which is instituted for the purpose of preventing race conditions.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] It is the requirement that one thread of execution never enters a critical section while a concurrent thread of execution is already accessing said critical section, which refers to an interval of time during which a thread of execution accesses a shared resource or shared memory.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] The shared resource is a data object, which two or more concurrent threads are trying to modify (where two concurrent read operations are permitted but, no two concurrent write operations or one read and one write are permitted, since it leads to data inconsistency).
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] The requirement of mutual exclusion was first identified and solved by Edsger W.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Dijkstra in his seminal 1965 paper "Solution of a problem in concurrent programming control", which is credited as the first topic in the study of concurrent algorithms.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] A simple example of why mutual exclusion is important in practice can be visualized using a singly linked list of four items, where the second and third are to be removed.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Although both removal operations complete successfully, the desired state of the linked list is not achieved: node *i* + 1 remains in the list, because the *next* pointer of node *i* – 1 points to node *i* + 1.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] This problem (called a *race condition*) can be avoided by using the requirement of mutual exclusion to ensure that simultaneous updates to the same part of the list cannot occur.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] The term mutual exclusion is also used in reference to the simultaneous writing of a memory address by one thread while the aforementioned memory address is being manipulated or read by one or more other threads.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] The problem which mutual exclusion addresses is a problem of resource sharing: how can a software system control multiple processes' access to a shared resource, when each process needs exclusive control of that resource while doing its work?
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] The mutual-exclusion solution to this makes the shared resource available only while the process is in a specific code segment called the critical section.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] It controls access to the shared resource by controlling each mutual execution of that part of its program where the resource would be used.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Every process's program can be partitioned into four sections, resulting in four states.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Operation is outside the critical section; the process is not using or requesting the shared resource.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] The process attempts to enter the critical section.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] The process is allowed to access the shared resource in this section.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] The process leaves the critical section and makes the shared resource available to other processes.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] If a process wishes to enter the critical section, it must first execute the trying section and wait until it acquires access to the critical section.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] After the process has executed its critical section and is finished with the shared resources, it needs to execute the exit section to release them for other processes' use.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] The process then returns to its non-critical section.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] On uni-processor systems, the simplest solution to achieve mutual exclusion is to disable interrupts during a process's critical section.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] This will prevent any interrupt service routines from running (effectively preventing a process from being preempted).
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Although this solution is effective, it leads to many problems.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] If a critical section is long, then the system clock will drift every time a critical section is executed because the timer interrupt is no longer serviced, so tracking time is impossible during the critical section.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Also, if a process halts during its critical section, control will never be returned to another process, effectively halting the entire system.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] A more elegant method for achieving mutual exclusion is the busy-wait.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Busy-waiting is effective for both uniprocessor and multiprocessor systems.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] The use of shared memory and an atomic test-and-set instruction provide the mutual exclusion.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] A process can test-and-set on a location in shared memory, and since the operation is atomic, only one process can set the flag at a time.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Any process that is unsuccessful in setting the flag can either go on to do other tasks and try again later, release the processor to another process and try again later, or continue to loop while checking the flag until it is successful in acquiring it.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Preemption is still possible, so this method allows the system to continue to function—even if a process halts while holding the lock.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Several other atomic operations can be used to provide mutual exclusion of data structures; most notable of these is compare-and-swap (CAS).
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] CAS can be used to achieve wait-free mutual exclusion for any shared data structure by creating a linked list where each node represents the desired operation to be performed.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] CAS is then used to change the pointers in the linked list during the insertion of a new node.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Only one process can be successful in its CAS; all other processes attempting to add a node at the same time will have to try again.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Each process can then keep a local copy of the data structure, and upon traversing the linked list, can perform each operation from the list on its local copy.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] In addition to hardware-supported solutions, some software solutions exist that use busy waiting to achieve mutual exclusion.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] These algorithms do not work if out-of-order execution is used on the platform that executes them.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Programmers have to specify strict ordering on the memory operations within a thread.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] It is often preferable to use synchronization facilities provided by an operating system’s multithreading library, which can take advantage of hardware support when available but fall back on software mechanisms when necessary.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] As a result, most modern mutual exclusion techniques aim to reduce latency and busy-waiting by relying on queuing and context switching.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] However, if the overhead of suspending and later restoring a thread is demonstrably greater than the time the thread would spend waiting for the lock to become available in a specific scenario, then spinlocks can be an acceptable solution in that context.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] One binary test&set register is sufficient to provide the deadlock-free solution to the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] But a solution built with a test&set register can possibly lead to the starvation of some processes which become caught in the trying section.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] In fact, $\Omega ({\sqrt {n}})$ distinct memory states are required to avoid lockout.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] To avoid unbounded waiting, *n* distinct memory states are required.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Most algorithms for mutual exclusion are designed with the assumption that no failure occurs while a process is running inside the critical section.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] However, in reality such failures may be commonplace.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] For example, a sudden loss of power or faulty interconnect might cause a process in a critical section to experience an unrecoverable error or otherwise be unable to continue.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] If such a failure occurs, conventional, non-failure-tolerant mutual exclusion algorithms may deadlock or otherwise fail key liveness properties.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] To deal with this problem, several solutions using crash-recovery mechanisms have been proposed.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Many forms of mutual exclusion have side-effects.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] For example, classic semaphores permit deadlocks, in which one process gets a semaphore, another process gets a second semaphore, and then both wait till the other semaphore to be released.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Other common side-effects include starvation, in which a process never gets sufficient resources to run to completion; priority inversion, in which a higher-priority thread waits for a lower-priority thread; and high latency, in which response to interrupts is not prompt.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Much research is aimed at eliminating the above effects, often with the goal of guaranteeing non-blocking progress.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Blocking system calls used to sleep an entire process.
[src:concurrency/mutual-exclusion] Until such calls became threadsafe, there was no proper mechanism for sleeping a single thread within a process (see polling).
[src:concurrency/process-computing] In computing, a **process** is the instance of a computer program that is being executed by one or many threads.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Depending on the OS, a process may be made up of multiple threads of execution that execute instructions concurrently.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] While a computer program is a passive collection of instructions typically stored in a file on disk, a process is the execution of those instructions after being loaded from the disk into memory.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Several processes may be associated with the same program; for example, opening up several instances of the same program often results in more than one process being executed.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Multitasking is a method to allow multiple processes to share processors (CPUs) and other system resources.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Each CPU (core) executes a single process at a time.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] However, multitasking allows each processor to switch between tasks that are being executed without having to wait for each task to finish (preemption).
[src:concurrency/process-computing] A common form of multitasking is provided by CPU's time-sharing that is a method for interleaving the execution of users' processes and threads, and even of independent kernel tasks – although the latter feature is feasible only in preemptive kernels such as Linux.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Preemption has an important side effect for interactive processes that are given higher priority with respect to CPU-bound processes; therefore users are immediately assigned computing resources at the simple pressing of a key or when moving a mouse.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Furthermore, applications like video and music reproduction are given some kind of real-time priority, preempting any other lower priority process.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] In time-sharing systems, context switches are performed rapidly, which makes it seem like multiple processes are being executed simultaneously on the same processor.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] This seemingly-simultaneous execution of multiple processes is called concurrency.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] For security and reliability, most modern operating systems prevent direct communication between independent processes, providing strictly mediated and controlled inter-process communication.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] The operating system holds most of this information about active processes in data structures called process control blocks.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Any subset of the resources, typically at least the processor state, may be associated with each of the process' threads in operating systems that support threads or *child* processes.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] The operating system keeps its processes separate and allocates the resources they need, so that they are less likely to interfere with each other and cause system failures (e.g., deadlock or thrashing).
[src:concurrency/process-computing] The operating system may also provide mechanisms for inter-process communication to enable processes to interact in safe and predictable ways.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] It is usual to associate a single process with a main program, and child processes with any spin-off, parallel processes, which behave like asynchronous subroutines.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] A process is said to *own* resources, of which an *image* of its program (in memory) is one such resource.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] However, in multiprocessing systems *many* processes may run off of, or share, the same reentrant program at the same location in memory, but each process is said to own its own *image* of the program.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Processes are often called "tasks" in embedded operating systems.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] The sense of "process" (or task) is "something that takes up time", as opposed to "memory", which is "something that takes up space".
[src:concurrency/process-computing] The above description applies to both processes managed by an operating system, and processes as defined by process calculi.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] If a process requests something for which it must wait, it will be blocked.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] When the process is in the blocked state, it is eligible for swapping to disk, but this is transparent in a virtual memory system, where regions of a process's memory may be really on disk and not in main memory at any time.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Even portions of active processes/tasks (executing programs) are eligible for swapping to disk, if the portions have not been used recently.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Not all parts of an executing program and its data have to be in physical memory for the associated process to be active.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] An operating system kernel that allows multitasking needs processes to have certain states.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Names for these states are not standardised, but they have similar functionality.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] When processes need to communicate with each other they must share parts of their address spaces or use other forms of inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:concurrency/process-computing] For instance in a shell pipeline, the output of the first process needs to pass to the second one, and so on.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] By the early 1960s, computer control software had evolved from monitor control software, for example IBSYS, to executive control software.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Over time, computers got faster while computer time was still neither cheap nor fully utilized; such an environment made multiprogramming possible and necessary.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Multiprogramming means that several programs run concurrently.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] At first, more than one program ran on a single processor, as a result of underlying uniprocessor computer architecture, and they shared scarce and limited hardware resources; consequently, the concurrency was of a *serial* nature.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] On later systems with multiple processors, multiple programs may run concurrently in *parallel*.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Programs consist of sequences of instructions for processors.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] A single processor can run only one instruction at a time: it is impossible to run more programs at the same time.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] A program might need some resource, such as an input device, which has a large delay, or a program might start some slow operation, such as sending output to a printer.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] This would lead to processor being "idle" (unused).
[src:concurrency/process-computing] To keep the processor busy at all times, the execution of such a program is halted and the operating system switches the processor to run another program.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] To the user, it will appear that the programs run at the same time (hence the term "parallel").
[src:concurrency/process-computing] Shortly thereafter, the notion of a "program" was expanded to the notion of an "executing program and its context".
[src:concurrency/process-computing] The concept of a process was born, which also became necessary with the invention of re-entrant code.
[src:concurrency/process-computing] However, with the advent of concepts such as time-sharing, computer networks, and multiple-CPU shared memory computers, the old "multiprogramming" gave way to true multitasking, multiprocessing and, later, multithreading.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] In computing, the **producer-consumer problem** (also known as the **bounded-buffer problem**) is a family of problems described by Edsger W.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra wrote about the unbounded buffer case: "We consider two processes, which are called the 'producer' and the 'consumer' respectively.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The producer is a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle it produces a certain portion of information, that has to be processed by the consumer.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The consumer is also a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle, it can process the next portion of information, as has been produced by the producer ...
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] He wrote about the bounded buffer case: "We have studied a producer and a consumer coupled via a buffer with unbounded capacity ...
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] And about the multiple producer-consumer case: "We consider a number of producer/consumer pairs, where pairi is coupled via an information stream containing ni portions.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen and Niklaus Wirth saw soon the problem of semaphores: "I have come to the same conclusion with regard to semaphores, namely that they are not suitable for higher level languages.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The original semaphore bounded buffer solution was written in ALGOL style.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The buffer can store N portions or elements.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The "number of queueing portions" semaphore counts the filled locations in the buffer, the "number of empty positions" semaphore counts the empty locations in the buffer and the semaphore "buffer manipulation" works as mutex for the buffer put and get operations.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is full, that is the number of empty positions is zero, the producer thread will wait in the P(number of empty positions) operation.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is empty, that is the number of queueing portions is zero, the consumer thread will wait in the P(number of queueing portions) operation.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operations release the semaphores.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] As a side effect, a thread can move from the wait queue to the ready queue.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The P() operation decreases the semaphore value down to zero.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operation increases the semaphore value.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] As of C++ 20, semaphores are part of the language.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra's solution can easily be written in modern C++.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The variable buffer_manipulation is a mutex.
