[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen defined the monitor: I will use the term monitor to denote a shared variable and the set of meaningful operations on it.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The purpose of a monitor is to control the scheduling of resources among individual processes according to a certain policy.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] Tony Hoare laid a theoretical foundation for the monitor.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor is an object that contains variables `buffer`, `head`, `tail` and `count` to realize a circular buffer, the condition variables `nonempty` and `nonfull` for synchronization and the methods `append` and `remove` to access the bounded buffer.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor operation wait corresponds to the semaphore operation P or acquire, signal corresponds to V or release.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The circled operation (+) are taken modulo N.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The presented Pascal style pseudo code shows a Hoare monitor.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] A Mesa monitor uses `while count` instead of `if count`.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The C++ version needs an additional mutex for technical reasons.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] It uses assert to enforce the preconditions for the buffer add and remove operations.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The very first producer-consumer solution in the Electrologica computers used 'channels'.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] Hoare defined channels: An alternative to explicit naming of source and destination would be to name a port through which communication is to take place.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The port names would be local to the processes, and the manner in which pairs of ports are to be connected by channels could be declared in the head of a parallel command.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] Brinch Hansen implemented channels in the programming languages Joyce and Super Pascal.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The Plan 9 operating system programming language Alef, the Inferno operating system programming language Limbo have channels.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The program entry point is at function `threadmain`.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The function call `ch = chancreate(sizeof(ulong), 1)` creates the channel, the function call `sendul(ch, i)` sends a value into the channel and the function call `p = recvul(ch)` receives a value from the channel.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The programming language Go has channels, too.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The Go producer-consumer solution uses the main Go routine for consumer and creates a new, unnamed Go routine for the producer.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The two Go routines are connected with channel ch.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] This channel can queue up to three int values.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The statement `ch := make(chan int, 3)` creates the channel, the statement `ch <- produceMessage()` sends a value into the channel and the statement `recvMsg := range ch` receives a value from the channel.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The allocation of memory resources, the allocation of processing resources, and the synchronization of resources are done by the programming language automatically.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] Leslie Lamport documented a bounded buffer producer-consumer solution for one producer and one consumer: We assume that the buffer can hold at most b messages, b >= 1.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] In our solution, we let k be a constant greater than b, and let s and r be integer variables assuming values between 0 and k-1.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] We assume that initially s=r and the buffer is empty.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] By choosing k to be a multiple of b, the buffer can be implemented as an array B [0: b - 1].
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The producer simply puts each new message into B[s mod b], and the consumer takes each message from B[r mod b].
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The algorithm is shown below, generalized for infinite k.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The Lamport solution uses busy waiting in the thread instead of waiting in the scheduler.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] This solution neglects the impact of scheduler thread switch at inconvenient times.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] If the first thread has read a variable value from memory, the scheduler switches to the second thread that changes the variable value, and the scheduler switches back to the first thread then the first thread uses the old value of the variable, not the current value.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] Atomic read-modify-write solves this problem.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] Modern C++ offers `atomic` variables and operations for multi-thread programming.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The following busy waiting C++11 solution for one producer and one consumer uses atomic read-modify-write operations `fetch_add` and `fetch_sub` on the atomic variable `count`.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The circular buffer index variables `head` and `tail` are thread-local and therefore not relevant for memory consistency.
[src:concurrency/producer-consumer-problem] The variable `count` controls the busy waiting of the producer and consumer thread.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A **race condition** or **race hazard** is the condition of an electronics, software, or other system where the system's substantive behavior is dependent on the sequence or timing of uncontrollable events, leading to unexpected or inconsistent results.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] It becomes a bug when one or more of the possible behaviors is undesirable.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] The term *race condition* was in use by 1954, for example in David A.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Huffman's doctoral thesis "The synthesis of sequential switching circuits".
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Race conditions can occur especially in logic circuits or concurrent or distributed software programs.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Using mutual exclusion can prevent race conditions.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A typical example of a race condition may occur when a logic gate combines signals that have traveled along different paths from the same source.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] The inputs to the gate can change at slightly different times in response to a change in the source signal.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] The output may, for a brief period, change to an unwanted state before settling back to the designed state.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Certain systems can tolerate such glitches, but if this output functions as a clock signal for further systems that contain memory, for example, the system can rapidly depart from its designed behaviour (in effect, the temporary glitch becomes a permanent glitch).
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Consider, for example, a two-input AND gate fed with the following logic: ${\text{output}}=A\wedge {\overline {A}}$ A logic signal A on one input and its Boolean negation ${\bar {A}}$ on another input can never, in theory, output a true value as $A\wedge {\overline {A}}\neq 1$ .
[src:concurrency/race-condition] If, however, changes in the value of A take longer to propagate to the second input than the first when A changes from false to true then a brief period will ensue during which both inputs are true, and so the gate's output will also be true.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A practical example of a race condition can occur when logic circuitry is used to detect certain outputs of a counter.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] If all the bits of the counter do not change exactly simultaneously, there will be intermediate patterns that can trigger false matches.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A *critical race condition* occurs when the order in which internal variables are changed determines the eventual state that the state machine will end up in.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A *non-critical race condition* occurs when the order in which internal variables are changed does not determine the eventual state that the state machine will end up in.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A *static race condition* occurs when a signal and its complement are combined.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A *dynamic race condition* occurs when it results in multiple transitions when only one is intended.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] They are due to interaction between gates.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] It can be eliminated by using no more than two levels of gating.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] An *essential race condition* occurs when an input has two transitions in less than the total feedback propagation time.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Sometimes they are cured using inductive delay line elements to effectively increase the time duration of an input signal.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Design techniques such as Karnaugh maps encourage designers to recognize and eliminate race conditions before they cause problems.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] By simplifying Boolean expressions and analyzing the relationships between input variables, designers can reduce the likelihood of unintended signal changes that may lead to race conditions.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] In many cases, logic redundancy can be intentionally added to digital circuits to eliminate certain types of races.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Although redundancy increases the number of logic gates, it can stabilize signal transitions and prevent temporary glitches that occur when signals change at slightly different times.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Engineers may also apply careful timing control and synchronization methods in sequential circuits.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] For example, using clocked elements such as flip-flops can help ensure that signals change in a predictable manner, reducing the risk of race conditions in complex digital systems.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Despite these precautions, some logic elements may still enter metastable states.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] In such cases, a circuit temporarily remains in an unstable condition between logical states, which can propagate uncertain signals through the system and create additional challenges for circuit designers.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A race condition can arise in software when a computer program has multiple code paths that are executing at the same time.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] If the multiple code paths take a different amount of time than expected, they can finish in a different order than expected, which can cause software bugs due to unanticipated behavior.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A race can also occur between two programs, resulting in security issues.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Critical race conditions cause invalid execution and software bugs and often happen when processes or threads depend on some shared state.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Operations upon shared states are done in critical sections that must be mutually exclusive.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Failure to obey this rule can corrupt the shared state.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A data race is a type of race condition.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Data races are important parts of various formal memory models.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] The memory model defined in the C11 and C++11 standards specify that a C or C++ program containing a data race has undefined behavior.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A race condition can be difficult to reproduce and debug because the result is nondeterministic and depends on the relative timing between interfering threads.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Problems of this nature can therefore disappear when running in debug mode, adding extra logging, or attaching a debugger.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A bug that disappears like this during debugging attempts is often referred to as a *Heisenbug*.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] It is therefore better to avoid race conditions by careful software design.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Assume that two threads each increment the value of a global integer variable by 1.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] In the case shown above, the final value is 2, as expected.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] However, if the two threads run simultaneously without locking or synchronization (via semaphores), the outcome of the operation could be wrong.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] In this case, the final value is 1 instead of the expected result of 2.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] This occurs because here the increment operations are not mutually exclusive.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Mutually exclusive operations are those that cannot be interrupted while accessing some resource such as a memory location.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Not everyone regards data races as a subset of race conditions.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] This implies that a data race is different from a race condition as it is possible to have nondeterminism due to timing even in a program without data races, for example, in a program in which all memory accesses use only atomic operations.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] On many platforms, special memory operations are provided for simultaneous access; in such cases, typically simultaneous access using these special operations is safe, but simultaneous access using other memory operations is dangerous.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Sometimes such special operations (which are safe for simultaneous access) are called *atomic* or *synchronization* operations, whereas the ordinary operations (which are unsafe for simultaneous access) are called *data* operations.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] This is probably why the term is *data* race; on many platforms, where there is a race condition involving only *synchronization* operations, such a race may be nondeterministic but otherwise safe; but a *data* race could lead to memory corruption or undefined behavior.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] The precise definition of data race differs across formal concurrency models.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] This matters because concurrent behavior is often non-intuitive and so formal reasoning is sometimes applied.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] The parts of this definition relating to signal handlers are idiosyncratic to C++ and are not typical of definitions of *data race*.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Here we have two memory operations accessing the same location, one of which is a write.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] If neither "X happens-before Y" nor "Y happens-before X", then we say that X and Y are "not ordered by the hb1 relation".
[src:concurrency/race-condition] So, the clause "... and they are not ordered by the hb1 relation of the execution" can be intuitively translated as "... and X and Y are potentially concurrent".
[src:concurrency/race-condition] The paper considers dangerous only those situations in which at least one of the memory operations is a *data operation*; in other parts of this paper, the paper also defines a class of *synchronization operations* which are safe for potentially simultaneous use, in contrast to *data operations*.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A critical difference between the C++ approach and the Java approach is that in C++, a data race is undefined behavior, whereas in Java, a data race merely affects *inter-thread actions*.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] An important facet of data races is that in some contexts, a program that is free of data races is guaranteed to execute in a sequentially consistent manner, greatly easing reasoning about the concurrent behavior of the program.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Formal memory models that provide such a guarantee are said to exhibit an SC for DRF (*sequential consistency for data race freedom*) property.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] This approach has been said to have achieved recent consensus (presumably compared to approaches that guarantee sequential consistency in all cases, or approaches which do not guarantee it at all).
[src:concurrency/race-condition] In other words, in C++, some correct programs are not sequentially consistent.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] This approach is thought to give C++ programmers the freedom to choose faster program execution at the cost of giving up ease of reasoning about their program.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] There are various theorems, often provided in the form of memory models, that provide SC for DRF guarantees given various contexts.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] The DRF1 memory model provides SC for DRF and allows the optimizations of the WO (weak ordering), RCsc (release consistency with sequentially consistent special operations), VAX memory model, and data-race-free-0 memory models.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] The PLpc memory model provides SC for DRF and allows the optimizations of the TSO (total store order), PSO, PC (processor consistency), and RCpc (release consistency with processor consistency special operations) models.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] DRFrlx provides a sketch of an SC for DRF theorem in the presence of relaxed atomics.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Many software race conditions have associated computer security implications.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A race condition allows an attacker with access to a shared resource to cause other actors that utilize that resource to malfunction, resulting in effects including denial of service and privilege escalation.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A specific kind of race condition involves checking for a predicate (e.g. for authentication), then acting on the predicate, while the state can change between the *time-of-check* and the *time-of-use*.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] When this kind of bug exists in security-sensitive code, a security vulnerability called a time-of-check to time-of-use (*TOCTTOU*) bug is created.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Race conditions are also intentionally used to create hardware random number generators and physically unclonable functions.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] PUFs can be created by designing circuit topologies with identical paths to a node and relying on manufacturing variations to randomly determine which paths will complete first.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] By measuring each manufactured circuit's specific set of race condition outcomes, a profile can be collected for each circuit and kept secret in order to later verify a circuit's identity.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Two or more programs may collide in their attempts to modify or access a file system, which can result in data corruption or privilege escalation.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] File locking provides a commonly used solution.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A more cumbersome remedy involves organizing the system in such a way that one unique process (running a daemon or the like) has exclusive access to the file, and all other processes that need to access the data in that file do so only via interprocess communication with that one process.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] This requires synchronization at the process level.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A different form of race condition exists in file systems where unrelated programs may affect each other by suddenly using up available resources such as disk space, memory space, or processor cycles.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Software not carefully designed to anticipate and handle this race situation may then become unpredictable.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Such a risk may be overlooked for a long time in a system that seems very reliable.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] But eventually enough data may accumulate or enough other software may be added to critically destabilize many parts of a system.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] An example of this occurred with the near loss of the Mars Rover "Spirit" not long after landing, which occurred due to deleted file entries causing the file system library to consume all available memory space.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A solution is for software to request and reserve all the resources it will need before beginning a task; if this request fails then the task is postponed, avoiding the many points where failure could have occurred.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Alternatively, each of those points can be equipped with error handling, or the success of the entire task can be verified afterwards, before continuing.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A more common approach is to simply verify that enough system resources are available before starting a task; however, this may not be adequate because in complex systems the actions of other running programs can be unpredictable.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] In networking, consider a distributed chat network like IRC, where a user who starts a channel automatically acquires channel-operator privileges.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] However, the latency across the network makes possible the kind of race condition described.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] In this case, heading off race conditions by imposing a form of control over access to the shared resource—say, appointing one server to control who holds what privileges—would mean turning the distributed network into a centralized one (at least for that one part of the network operation).
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Race conditions can also exist when a computer program is written with non-blocking sockets, in which case the performance of the program can be dependent on the speed of the network link.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Software flaws in life-critical systems can be disastrous.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Race conditions were among the flaws in the Therac-25 radiation therapy machine, which led to the death of at least three patients and injuries to several more.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Another example is the energy management system provided by GE Energy and used by Ohio-based FirstEnergy Corp (among other power facilities).
[src:concurrency/race-condition] A race condition existed in the alarm subsystem; when three sagging power lines were tripped simultaneously, the condition prevented alerts from being raised to the monitoring technicians, delaying their awareness of the problem.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] This software flaw eventually led to the North American Blackout of 2003.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] GE Energy later developed a software patch to correct the previously undiscovered error.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Many software tools exist to help detect race conditions in software.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] They can be largely categorized into two groups: static analysis tools and dynamic analysis tools.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Thread Safety Analysis is a static analysis tool for annotation-based intra-procedural static analysis, originally implemented as a branch of gcc, and now reimplemented in Clang, supporting PThreads.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Race conditions are a common concern in human-computer interaction design and software usability.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] In UK railway signalling, a race condition would arise in the carrying out of Rule 55.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] According to this rule, if a train was stopped on a running line by a signal, the locomotive fireman would walk to the signal box in order to remind the signalman that the train was present.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] In at least one case, at Winwick in 1934, an accident occurred because the signalman accepted another train before the fireman arrived.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Modern signalling practice removes the race condition by making it possible for the driver to instantaneously contact the signal box by radio.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Race conditions are not confined to digital systems.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] Neuroscience is demonstrating that race conditions can occur in mammal brains as well.
[src:concurrency/race-condition] One demonstrated race is between neural pathways that execute planned movement and separate pathways that can cancel said movement.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] In computer science, a **semaphore** is a variable or abstract data type used to control access to a common resource that is being accessed by multiple threads and avoid critical section problems in a concurrent system such as a multitasking operating system.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Semaphores are a type of synchronization primitive.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] A trivial semaphore is a plain variable that is changed (for example, incremented or decremented, or toggled) depending on programmer-defined conditions.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Though semaphores are useful for preventing race conditions, they do not guarantee their absence.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Semaphores that allow an arbitrary resource count are called **counting semaphores**, while semaphores that are restricted to the values 0 and 1 (or locked/unlocked, unavailable/available) are called **binary semaphores** and are used to implement locks.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The semaphore concept was invented by Dutch computer scientist Edsger Dijkstra in 1962 or 1963, when Dijkstra and his team were developing an operating system for the Electrologica X8.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] That system eventually became known as the THE multiprogramming system.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Suppose a physical library has ten identical study rooms, to be used by one student at a time.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Students must request a room from the front desk.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] If no rooms are free, students wait at the desk until someone relinquishes a room.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] When a student has finished using a room, the student must return to the desk and indicate that the room is free.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] In the simplest implementation, the clerk at the front desk knows only the number of free rooms available.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] This requires that all of the students use their room while they have signed up for it and return it when they are done.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] When a student requests a room, the clerk decreases this number.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] When a student releases a room, the clerk increases this number.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The room can be used as long as desired and rooms cannot be booked in advance.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] In this scenario, the front desk count-holder represents a counting semaphore, the rooms are the resource, and the students represent processes/threads.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The value of the semaphore in this scenario is initially 10, with all rooms empty.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] When a student requests a room, they are granted access, and the value of the semaphore is changed to 9.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] After the next student comes, it drops to 8, then 7, and so on.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] If someone requests a room and the current value of the semaphore is 0, they are forced to wait until a room is freed (when the count is increased from 0).
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] If one of the rooms was released, but there are several students waiting, any method can be used to select the one who will occupy the room (like FIFO or random selection).
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] And of course, a student must inform the clerk about releasing their room only after leaving it.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] When used to control access to a pool of resources, a semaphore tracks only *how many* resources are free.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] It does not keep track of *which* of the resources are free.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Some other mechanism (possibly involving more semaphores) may be required to select a particular free resource.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The paradigm is especially powerful because the semaphore count may serve as a useful trigger for a number of different actions.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The librarian above may turn the lights off in the study hall when there are no students remaining, or may place a sign that says the rooms are very busy when most of the rooms are occupied.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The success of the protocol requires applications to follow it correctly.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Fairness and safety are likely to be compromised (which practically means a program may behave slowly, act erratically, hang, or crash) if even a single process acts incorrectly.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Even if all processes follow these rules, *multi-resource deadlock* may still occur when there are different resources managed by different semaphores and when processes need to use more than one resource at a time, as illustrated by the dining philosophers problem.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Counting semaphores are equipped with two operations, historically denoted as P and V (see § Operation names for alternative names).
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Operation V increments the semaphore *S*, and operation P decrements it.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The value of the semaphore *S* represents the number of units of available resource units when non-negative.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] In some implementations, negative values indicate the number of processes waiting for the resource.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The P operation wastes time or sleeps until a resource protected by the semaphore becomes available, at which time the resource is immediately claimed.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The V operation is the inverse: it makes a resource available again after the process has finished using it.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] One important property of semaphore *S* is that its value cannot be changed except by using the V and P operations.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Many operating systems provide efficient semaphore primitives that unblock a waiting process when the semaphore is incremented.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] This means that processes do not waste time checking the semaphore value unnecessarily.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The counting semaphore concept can be extended with the ability to claim or return more than one "unit" from the semaphore, a technique implemented in Unix.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] However, the rest of this section refers to semaphores with unary V and P operations, unless otherwise specified.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] To avoid starvation, a semaphore has an associated queue of processes (usually with FIFO semantics).
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] If a process performs a P operation on a semaphore that has the value zero, the process is added to the semaphore's queue and its execution is suspended.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] When another process increments the semaphore by performing a V operation, and there are processes on the queue, one of them is removed from the queue and resumes execution.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] When processes have different priorities the queue may be ordered thereby, such that the highest priority process is taken from the queue first.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] If the implementation does not ensure atomicity of the increment, decrement, and comparison operations, there is a risk of increments or decrements being forgotten, or of the semaphore value becoming negative.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Atomicity may be achieved by using a machine instruction that can read, modify, and write the semaphore in a single operation.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Without such a hardware instruction, an atomic operation may be synthesized by using a software mutual exclusion algorithm.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] On uniprocessor systems, atomic operations can be ensured by temporarily suspending preemption or disabling hardware interrupts.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] This approach does not work on multiprocessor systems where it is possible for two programs sharing a semaphore to run on different processors at the same time.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] To solve this problem in a multiprocessor system, a locking variable can be used to control access to the semaphore.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The locking variable is manipulated using a test-and-set-lock command.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Consider a variable *A* and a Boolean variable *S*.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] *A* is only accessed when *S* is marked true.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] One can imagine a stoplight signal (*S*) just before a train station (*A*).
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] In this case, if the signal is green, then one can enter the train station.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] If it is yellow or red (or any other color), the train station cannot be accessed.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Consider a system that can only support ten users (S=10).
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Whenever a user logs in, P is called, decrementing the semaphore *S* by 1.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Whenever a user logs out, V is called, incrementing *S* by 1 representing a login slot that has become available.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] When *S* is 0, any users wishing to log in must wait until *S* increases.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The login request is enqueued onto a FIFO queue until a slot is freed.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Mutual exclusion is used to ensure that requests are enqueued in order.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Whenever *S* increases (login slots available), a login request is dequeued, and the user owning the request is allowed to log in.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] If *S* is already greater than 0, then login requests are immediately dequeued.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] In the producer–consumer problem, one process (the producer) generates data items and another process (the consumer) receives and uses them.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The semaphore solution to the producer–consumer problem tracks the state of the queue with two semaphores: `emptyCount`, the number of empty places in the queue, and `fullCount`, the number of elements in the queue.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] To maintain integrity, `emptyCount` may be lower (but never higher) than the actual number of empty places in the queue, and `fullCount` may be lower (but never higher) than the actual number of items in the queue.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Empty places and items represent two kinds of resources, empty boxes and full boxes, and the semaphores `emptyCount` and `fullCount` maintain control over these resources.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The binary semaphore `useQueue` ensures that the integrity of the state of the queue itself is not compromised, for example, by two producers attempting to add items to an empty queue simultaneously, thereby corrupting its internal state.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Alternatively a mutex could be used in place of the binary semaphore.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The `emptyCount` is initially *N*, `fullCount` is initially 0, and `useQueue` is initially 1.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Several producers enter the producer critical section.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] No more than *N* producers may enter their critical section due to `emptyCount` constraining their entry.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The producers, one at a time, gain access to the queue through `useQueue` and deposit items in the queue.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Once the first producer exits its critical section, `fullCount` is incremented, allowing one consumer to enter its critical section.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Note that `emptyCount` may be much lower than the actual number of empty places in the queue, for example, where many producers have decremented it but are waiting their turn on `useQueue` before filling empty places.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Note that `emptyCount + fullCount ≤ *N*` always holds, with equality if and only if no producers or consumers are executing their critical sections.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The "Passing the baton" pattern proposed by Gregory R.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Andrews is a generic scheme to solve many complex concurrent programming problems in which multiple processes compete for the same resource with complex access conditions (such as satisfying specific priority criteria or avoiding starvation).
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Given a shared resource, the pattern requires a private "priv" semaphore (initialized to zero) for each process (or class of processes) involved and a single mutual exclusion "mutex" semaphore (initialized to one).
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The pattern is called "passing the baton" because a process that releases the resource as well as a freshly reactivated process will activate at most one suspended process, that is, shall "pass the baton to it".
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The mutex is released only when a process is going to suspend itself (resource_acquire), or when pass_the_baton is unable to reactivate another suspended process.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] The canonical names V and P come from the initials of Dutch words.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] V is generally explained as *verhogen* ("increase").
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Several explanations have been offered for P, including *proberen* ("to test" or "to try"), *passeren* ("pass"), and *pakken* ("grab").
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Dijkstra's earliest paper on the subject gives *passering* ("passing") as the meaning for *P*, and *vrijgave* ("release") as the meaning for V.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] It also mentions that the terminology is taken from that used in railroad signals.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Dijkstra subsequently wrote that he intended *P* to stand for *prolaag*, short for *probeer te verlagen*, literally "try to reduce", or to parallel the terms used in the other case, "try to decrease".
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] In ALGOL 68, the Linux kernel, and in some English textbooks, the *V* and *P* operations are called, respectively, *up* and *down*.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] In software engineering practice, they are often called *signal* and *wait*, *release* and *acquire* (standard Java library), or *post* and *pend*.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Some texts call them *vacate* and *procure* to match the original Dutch initials.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] A mutex is a locking mechanism that sometimes uses the same basic implementation as the binary semaphore.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] However, they differ in how they are used.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] While a binary semaphore may be colloquially referred to as a mutex, a true mutex has a more specific use-case and definition, in that only the task that locked the mutex is supposed to unlock it.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Premature task termination: Mutexes may also provide deletion safety, where the task holding the mutex cannot be accidentally deleted.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Termination deadlock: If a mutex-holding task terminates for any reason, the OS can release the mutex and signal waiting tasks of this condition.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Recursion deadlock: a task is allowed to lock a reentrant mutex multiple times as it unlocks it an equal number of times.
[src:concurrency/semaphore-programming] Accidental release: An error is raised on the release of the mutex if the releasing task is not its owner.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] In computer science, a **thread** of execution is the smallest sequence of programmed instructions that can be managed independently by a scheduler, which is typically a part of the operating system.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] In many cases, a thread is a component of a process.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The multiple threads of a given process may be executed concurrently (via multithreading capabilities), sharing resources such as memory, while different processes do not share these resources.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] In particular, the threads of a process share its executable code and the values of its dynamically allocated variables and non-thread-local global variables at any given time.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The implementation of threads and processes differs between operating systems.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Threads made an early appearance under the name of "tasks" in IBM's batch processing operating system, OS/360, in 1967.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] It provided users with three available configurations of the OS/360 control system, of which multiprogramming with a variable number of tasks (MVT) was one.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The Mach implementation of threads was described in the summer of 1986.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] OS/2 1.0, released in 1987, supported threads.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Digital Research's MP/M operating system provided multiprogramming, multi-tasking, and preemptive multi-tasking for the Intel 8080 processor in 1979, and on the 8086 processor in 1981.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The first version of Windows to have threads was Windows NT, which was released in 1993.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] In 1995, the IEEE defined the pthreads API, which standardized an interface for portable multithreaded programming across a variety of Unix-like operating systems.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Since then, pthreads has also been implemented on Windows with third-party packages such as *pthreads-w32*, which implements the standard on top of the existing Windows API.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The use of threads in software applications became more common in the early 2000s as CPUs began to utilize multiple cores.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Applications wishing to take advantage of multiple cores for performance advantages were required to employ concurrency to utilize the multiple cores.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Scheduling can be done at the kernel level or user level, and multitasking can be done preemptively or cooperatively.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] This yields a variety of related concepts.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] At the kernel level, a *process* contains one or more *kernel threads*, which share the process's resources, such as memory and file handles – a process is a unit of resources, while a thread is a unit of scheduling and execution.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Kernel scheduling is typically uniformly done preemptively or, less commonly, cooperatively.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] At the user level a process such as a runtime system can itself schedule multiple threads of execution.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] If these do not share data, as in Erlang, they are usually analogously called processes, while if they share data they are usually called *(user) threads*, particularly if preemptively scheduled.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Cooperatively scheduled user threads are known as *fibers*; different processes may schedule user threads differently.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] User threads may be executed by kernel threads in various ways (one-to-one, many-to-one, many-to-many).
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The term *light-weight process* variously refers to user threads or to kernel mechanisms for scheduling user threads onto kernel threads.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] A process is a heavyweight unit of kernel scheduling, as creating, destroying, and switching processes is relatively expensive.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Processes own resources allocated by the operating system.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Resources include memory (for both code and data), file handles, sockets, device handles, windows, and a process control block.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Processes are *isolated* by process isolation, and do not share address spaces or file resources except through explicit methods such as inheriting file handles or shared memory segments, or mapping the same file in a shared way – see Interprocess communication.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Creating or destroying a process is relatively expensive, as resources must be acquired or released.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] A *kernel thread* is a lightweight unit of kernel scheduling.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] At least one kernel thread exists within each process.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] If multiple kernel threads exist within a process, then they share the same memory and file resources.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Kernel threads are preemptively multitasked if the operating system's process scheduler is preemptive.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Kernel threads do not own resources except for a stack, a copy of the registers including the program counter, and thread-local storage (if any), and are thus relatively cheap to create and destroy.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Thread switching is also relatively cheap: it requires a context switch (saving and restoring registers and stack pointer), but does not change virtual memory and is thus cache-friendly (leaving TLB valid).
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The kernel can assign one or more software threads to each core in a CPU (it being able to assign itself multiple software threads depending on its support for multithreading), and can swap out threads that get blocked.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] However, kernel threads take much longer than user threads to be swapped.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Threads are sometimes implemented in userspace libraries, thus called *user threads*.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The kernel is unaware of them, so they are managed and scheduled in userspace.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Some implementations base their user threads on top of several kernel threads, to benefit from multi-processor machines (M:N model).
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] User threads as implemented by virtual machines are also called green threads.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Since scheduling occurs in userspace, the scheduling policy can be more easily tailored to the requirements of the program's workload.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] However, the use of blocking system calls in user threads (as opposed to kernel threads) can be problematic.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] If a user thread or a fiber performs a system call that blocks, the other user threads and fibers in the process are unable to run until the system call returns.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] A typical example of this problem is when performing I/O: most programs are written to perform I/O synchronously.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] When an I/O operation is initiated, a system call is made, and does not return until the I/O operation has been completed.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] In the intervening period, the entire process is "blocked" by the kernel and cannot run, which starves other user threads and fibers in the same process from executing.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Similar solutions can be provided for other blocking system calls.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Alternatively, the program can be written to avoid the use of synchronous I/O or other blocking system calls (in particular, using non-blocking I/O, including lambda continuations and/or async/await primitives).
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Fibers are an even lighter unit of scheduling which are cooperatively scheduled: a running fiber must explicitly *yield* to allow another fiber to run, which makes their implementation much easier than kernel or user threads.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] A fiber can be scheduled to run in any thread in the same process.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] This permits applications to gain performance improvements by managing scheduling themselves, instead of relying on the kernel scheduler (which may not be tuned for the application).
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Some research implementations of the OpenMP parallel programming model implement their tasks through fibers.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Closely related to fibers are coroutines, with the distinction being that coroutines are a language-level construct, while fibers are a system-level construct.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Operating systems schedule threads either preemptively or cooperatively.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Multi-user operating systems generally favor preemptive multithreading for its finer-grained control over execution time via context switching.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] However, preemptive scheduling may context-switch threads at moments unanticipated by programmers, thus causing lock convoy, priority inversion, or other side-effects.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] In contrast, cooperative multithreading relies on threads to relinquish control of execution, thus ensuring that threads run to completion.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] This can cause problems if a cooperatively-multitasked thread blocks by waiting on a resource or if it starves other threads by not yielding control of execution during intensive computation.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Until the early 2000s, most desktop computers had only one single-core CPU, with no support for hardware threads, although threads were still used on such computers because switching between threads was generally still quicker than full-process context switches.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] In 2002, Intel added support for simultaneous multithreading to the Pentium 4 processor, under the name *hyper-threading*; in 2005, they introduced the dual-core Pentium D processor and AMD introduced the dual-core Athlon 64 X2 processor.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Systems with a single processor generally implement multithreading by time slicing: the central processing unit (CPU) switches between different *software threads*.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] This context switching usually occurs frequently enough that users perceive the threads or tasks as running in parallel (for popular server/desktop operating systems, maximum time slice of a thread, when other threads are waiting, is often limited to 100–200ms).
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] On a multiprocessor or multi-core system, multiple threads can execute in parallel, with every processor or core executing a separate thread simultaneously; on a processor or core with *hardware threads*, separate software threads can also be executed concurrently by separate hardware threads.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Threads created by the user in a 1:1 correspondence with schedulable entities in the kernel are the simplest possible threading implementation.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] OS/2 and Win32 used this approach from the start, while on Linux the GNU C Library implements this approach (via the NPTL or older LinuxThreads).
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] This approach is also used by Solaris, NetBSD, FreeBSD, macOS, and iOS.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] An *M*:1 model implies that all application-level threads map to one kernel-level scheduled entity; the kernel has no knowledge of the application threads.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] With this approach, context switching can be done very quickly and, in addition, it can be implemented even on simple kernels which do not support threading.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] One of the major drawbacks, however, is that it cannot benefit from the hardware acceleration on multithreaded processors or multi-processor computers: there is never more than one thread being scheduled at the same time.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] For example: If one of the threads needs to execute an I/O request, the whole process is blocked and the threading advantage cannot be used.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The GNU Portable Threads uses User-level threading, as does State Threads.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] SunOS 4.x implemented *light-weight processes* or LWPs.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] NetBSD 2.x+, and DragonFly BSD implement LWPs as kernel threads (1:1 model).
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] SunOS 5.2 through SunOS 5.8 as well as NetBSD 2 to NetBSD 4 implemented a two level model, multiplexing one or more user level threads on each kernel thread (M:N model).
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] SunOS 5.9 and later, as well as NetBSD 5 eliminated user threads support, returning to a 1:1 model.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] FreeBSD 6 supported both 1:1 and M:N, users could choose which one should be used with a given program using /etc/libmap.conf.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Starting with FreeBSD 7, the 1:1 became the default.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] FreeBSD 8 no longer supports the M:N model.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] In computer programming, *single-threading* is the processing of one instruction at a time.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] In the formal analysis of the variables' semantics and process state, the term *single threading* can be used differently to mean "backtracking within a single thread", which is common in the functional programming community.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Multithreading is mainly found in multitasking operating systems.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Multithreading is a widespread programming and execution model that allows multiple threads to exist within the context of one process.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] These threads share the process's resources, but are able to execute independently.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The threaded programming model provides developers with a useful abstraction of concurrent execution.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Multithreading can also be applied to one process to enable parallel execution on a multiprocessing system.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Multithreading libraries tend to provide a function call to create a new thread, which takes a function as a parameter.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] A concurrent thread is then created which starts running the passed function and ends when the function returns.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] The thread libraries also offer data synchronization functions.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Threads in the same process share the same address space.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] This allows concurrently running code to couple tightly and conveniently exchange data without the overhead or complexity of an IPC.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] When shared between threads, however, even simple data structures become prone to race conditions if they require more than one CPU instruction to update: two threads may end up attempting to update the data structure at the same time and find it unexpectedly changing underfoot.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Bugs caused by race conditions can be very difficult to reproduce and isolate.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] To prevent this, threading application programming interfaces (APIs) offer synchronization primitives such as mutexes to lock data structures against concurrent access.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] On uniprocessor systems, a thread running into a locked mutex must sleep and hence trigger a context switch.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] On multi-processor systems, the thread may instead poll the mutex in a spinlock.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Both of these may sap performance and force processors in symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) systems to contend for the memory bus, especially if the granularity of the locking is too fine.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Other synchronization APIs include condition variables, critical sections, semaphores, and monitors.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] A popular programming pattern involving threads is that of thread pools where a set number of threads are created at startup that then wait for a task to be assigned.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] When a new task arrives, it wakes up, completes the task and goes back to waiting.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] This avoids the relatively expensive thread creation and destruction functions for every task performed and takes thread management out of the application developer's hand and leaves it to a library or the operating system that is better suited to optimize thread management.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] If all threads are busy, additional work items are placed in a queue until a thread becomes available to execute them.
[src:concurrency/thread-computing] Many programming languages support threading in some capacity.
